    <div class="faq__list">
      <details class="faq__item">
      <summary class="faq__q">
  <span>How is Reviv different from braces? </span>
</summary>


        <div class="faq__a">
          Braces force your teeth into a new position using artificial mechanical pressure — a position the skull never agreed to. This is why retainers are needed afterward: the teeth want to go back. Braces don't fix the underlying structure; they fight it. And over time, that fight causes real damage — root resorption, skull compression, and cascading health issues down the road.

Reviv works with your body, not against it. Instead of moving teeth, it gently restores the natural curve of the bite, which allows the skull to re-expand and the jaw to find its correct position on its own. No force. No retainers needed. No damage. Just physics
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary class="faq__q">
          <span>How long does it take to see results?</span>
        
        </summary>
        <div class="faq__a">
          It depends on where you're starting from and what you're trying to achieve. Many people notice early improvements — less pain, better sleep, reduced brain fog — within the first few weeks to a few months. For someone who isn't in bad shape and just wants to get out of their main symptoms, a few months of consistent use can be enough.



For deeper structural recovery, it's a longer game — think years, not weeks. The body has been compensating for a long time, and unwinding those compensations takes time. The good news is that most people feel meaningful progress well before they're "done," and the process keeps working as long as you stay consistent.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary class="faq__q">
          <span>What if I'm not experiencing health issues from my braces?</span>
          
        </summary>
        <div class="faq__a">
          That's actually very common — the damage from braces rarely shows up right away. The effects typically unfold gradually over 10–20 years as the teeth continue to shift into unstable positions and slowly wear down. Most people don't connect the dots because the timeline is so long.

What tends to happen isn't always dramatic pain. More often it's subtle: a face that slowly loses its definition, a body that gets harder to keep in shape, focus that isn't quite as sharp, energy that isn't what it used to be. Things that are easy to chalk up to "just getting older."

Reviv isn't just for people in crisis. It's also for people who want to get ahead of the curve — restore what was taken from the structure before the decline gets harder to reverse.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary class="faq__q">
          <span>How does it work exactly?</span>

        </summary>
        <div class="faq__a">
          Your teeth aren't just for chewing — they're structural supports for your entire skull. When teeth wear down, get moved by braces, or lose height from dental work, the natural curve of the back teeth (called the "curve of spee") flattens. That's where the problem starts.



Think of your skull like a balloon. When that curve flattens, the balloon deflates — the skull compresses inward, putting pressure on the brain, twisting the spine, and displacing organs. Most people experience this as a slow, gradual decline they blame on age or genetics.



Wearing Reviv restores height to the back teeth, which re-establishes that curve. This begins to re-inflate the balloon. As the soft tissue of the skull gradually stretches back out, the compression releases — and with it, the cascade of health issues that followed.

It's more like physics that impact the entire body than dentistry. No force is applied to move teeth. You're simply giving the structure what it needs to find its way back.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
